Definition 2.1 ([2]). The $n$th cross effect of a functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ between two abelian categories, where the zero object of $\mathcal{A}$ is denoted by $0$, is the functor $\mathrm{cr}_{n}F\colon\mathcal{A}^{n}\to\mathcal{B}$ defined recursively by $F(x)\cong F(0)\oplus\mathrm{cr}_{1}F(x)$ $\mathrm{cr}_{1}F(x_{1}\oplus x_{2})\cong\mathrm{cr}_{1}F(x_{1})\oplus\mathrm{% cr}_{1}F(x_{2})\oplus\mathrm{cr}_{2}F(x_{1},x_{2})$ and in general, $\displaystyle\mathrm{cr}_{n-1}F(x_{1}\oplus x_{2},x_{3},\ldots,x_{n})\cong$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{cr}_{n-1}F(x_{1},x_{3},\ldots,x_{n})\oplus\mathrm{cr}_{n-% 1}F(x_{2},x_{3},\ldots,x_{n})$ $\displaystyle\oplus\mathrm{cr}_{n}F(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}),$ where $\oplus$ denotes the biproduct in both categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ (a common abuse of notation).
Definition 2.4. [1, Definition 5.1] The linearization of an abelian functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ is the (abelian) functor $D_{1}F\colon\mathcal{A}\to{Ch}\mathcal{B}$ given as the explicit chain complex $(D_{1}F_{*},\partial_{*})$ where: $(D_{1}F)_{k}\coloneqq\begin{cases}C_{2}^{\times k}F&k\geq 1\\ \mathrm{cr}_{1}F&k=0\\ 0&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}$ and $C_{2}^{\times k}$ is the functor $C_{2}=\mathrm{cr}_{2}\circ diag$ composed with itself $k$ times. The chain differential $\partial_{1}\colon(D_{1}F)_{1}\to(D_{1}F)_{0}$ is given by the map $\epsilon$ of [1, Remark 2.8], and the chain differential $\partial_{k}\colon(D_{1}F)_{k}\to(D_{1}F)_{k-1}$ is given by $\sum_{i=1}^{k}(-1)^{i}C_{2}^{\times i}\epsilon$ when $k\geq 1$, where $\epsilon$ is the counit of the adjunction of [1, Corollary 2.7].
Definition 2.7. [1, Lemma 6.3] For an abelian functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ with objects $x$ and $v$ in $\mathcal{A}$, define $\nabla F(v;x)\mathrel{:=}D_{1}F(x\oplus-)(v).$
Definition 2.3. An abelian functor $F:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ is degree n if $\mathrm{cr}_{n+1}F\simeq 0.$ In particular, $F$ is degree 1 if $\mathrm{cr}_{2}F\simeq 0$. If $F$ is also reduced, meaning that $F(0)\simeq 0$, then we say that $F$ is linear. We call $F$ strictly reduced if $F(0)\simeq 0$ is a chain homotopy equivalence.
Definition 2.8. [1, Definition 7.3] Consider an abelian functor $F:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ and objects $x$, $v$, and $w$ in $\mathcal{A}$. The higher order directional derivatives of $F$ are defined recursively by $\displaystyle\Delta_{0}F(x)$ $\displaystyle\mathrel{:=}F(x),$ $\displaystyle\Delta_{1}F(v;x)$ $\displaystyle\mathrel{:=}\nabla F(v;x),$ $\displaystyle\Delta_{2}F(w,v;x)$ $\displaystyle\mathrel{:=}\nabla(\Delta_{1}F)\left((w;v);(v;x)\right).$ We say that $\Delta_{1}F(v;x)$ is the first directional derivative of $F$ at $x$ in the direction $v$. Similarly, we say that $\Delta_{2}F(w,v;x)$ is the second higher order directional derivative of $F$ at $x$ in the directions $v$ and $w$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\omega\in H^{3}(\Lambda,\Bbbk^{\times})$. We say that $\omega$ is trivializable if it satisfies one of the equivalent conditions of Theorem 3.2. If $p:\Gamma\to\Lambda$ is an epimorphism of abelian groups such that the pullback $p^{*}\omega\in H^{3}(\Gamma,\Bbbk^{\times})$ is trivial, we say that $\omega$ is $p$-trivial.
Definition 4.4 (Morphisms between centered spaces). A function $f\colon X\to Y$ between two centered spaces $(X,\nu_{X})$ and $(Y,\nu_{Y})$ is called centered at $x\in X$ if $f(\nu_{X}(x))\preceq\nu_{Y}(f(x))$. A function which is centered at each $x\in X$ will be simply called centered.
Definition 3.1. Given $f,g\in Y^{X}$ we say $f$ is $\mathcal{P}$-related to $g$, and we write $f\hat{\mathcal{P}}g$, if the coincidence set of $f$ and $g$ belongs to $\mathcal{P}$. In other words, $f\hat{\mathcal{P}}g$ if $\{x\in X\mid f(x)=g(x)\}\in\mathcal{P}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $X$ and $\mathcal{P}$ be as above. Then: $\mathcal{P}\text{ is a }\begin{cases}\text{raster}\\ \text{filterbase}\\ \text{filter}\end{cases}\text{ on $X$ if it satisfies Conditions }\begin{cases% }\ref{defn:filter0},\ref{defn:filter1}\\ \ref{defn:filter0},\ref{defn:filter2}\\ \ref{defn:filter0},\ref{defn:filter1},\ref{defn:filter2}\end{cases}.$
Definition 3.5. Given $f,g\in Y^{X}$ we say $f$ is weakly $\mathcal{P}$-related to $g$, and we write $f\hat{\mathcal{P}}_{w}g$, if the coincidence set of $f$ and $g$ contains an element of $\mathcal{P}$. In other words, $f\hat{\mathcal{P}}_{w}g$ if there is $P\in\mathcal{P}$ such that $P\subset\{x\in X\mid f(x)=g(x)\}$.
Definition 4.1 (Centered spaces). A centered structure on a set $X$ is given by assigning to each point $x\in X$ a collection $\nu(x)$ of subsets of $X$ with the property that $x\in N$ for each $N\in\nu(x)$. A set together with a centered structure is called a centered space.
Definitions 5.1.2. [11, Def. C2.1.1, Theorem D3.3.1] A coverage $\mathcal{J}$ on a small category $\mathcal{C}$ is regular if it is generated by singleton covering families. A Grothendieck topos $\mathcal{E}$ is a regular topos if there exists a small lex category $\mathcal{C}$ and a regular coverage $\mathcal{J}$ on $\mathcal{C}$ such that $\mathcal{E}\simeq\operatorname{Sh}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{J})$. A geometric morphism $e_{*}:\mathcal{E}_{1}\leftrightarrows\mathcal{E}_{2}:e^{*}$ between two regular toposes is regular if the inverse image functor $e^{*}$ preserves regular objects.
Definitions 3.1.2. A category $\mathcal{B}$ is regular if it is lex, it admits coequalizers of kernel pairs of all its morphisms, and in which regular epimorphisms are stable under pullbacks. A functor between $b:\mathcal{B}_{1}\to\mathcal{B}_{2}$ two regular categories is regular if it is lex and preserves regular epimorphisms. A regular category $\mathcal{B}$ is exact (in the sense of Barr) if every equivalence relation is a kernel pair of some morphism.
Definition 2.3.2. Suppose $\mathcal{K}$ is a locally finitely presentable category. An $(\omega,\lambda)$-injectivity class in $\mathcal{K}$ is a full subcategory of $\mathcal{K}$ consisting of objects injective to a set of morphisms having finitely presentable domain and $\lambda$-presentable codomain.
Definitions 4.2.1. [20, §3.4.1] A full subcategory $\mathcal{D}$ of $R\mbox{-}\operatorname{Mod}$ is definable if there is a set $\{\phi_{\lambda}(x)/\psi_{\lambda}(x)\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$ of pairs of pp-formulas in one variable satisfying $\phi_{\lambda}(x)\rightarrow\psi_{\lambda}(x)$ for each $\lambda$ such that $\mathcal{D}$ is precisely the subcategory of modules such that $\phi_{\lambda}(M)=\psi_{\lambda}(M)$ for each $\lambda\in\Lambda$.
Definition 2.2.1. A category is called predefinable if it has products and directed colimits and products distribute over directed colimits.
Definition 3.2.1. (cf. Definition 4.3.1) A category $\mathcal{L}$ is exactly definable if there exists a small exact category $\mathcal{B}$ such that $\mathcal{L}$ is equivalent to the category $\operatorname{Reg}(\mathcal{B},\operatorname{Set})$ of regular functors on $\mathcal{B}$.
Definitions 2.1.1. A full subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of a locally finitely presentable category $\mathcal{K}$ is a definable subcategory if it is closed in $\mathcal{K}$ under products, directed colimits and pure subobjects. Furthermore, a category is definable if it is equivalent to a definable subcategory of a locally finitely presentable category. A functor between two definable categories is an interpretation functor if it preserves products and directed colimits.
Definitions 4.4.1. An object $A$ of an abelian category $\mathcal{A}$ with directed colimits is coherent if it is finitely presentable and each of its finitely generated subobjects is finitely presentable. An abelian category $\mathcal{G}$ with directed colimits is locally coherent if it has a generating set consisting of coherent objects. A coherent morphism $f:\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{G}^{\prime}$ between locally coherent categories is a pair of adjoint functors $f_{*}:\mathcal{G}\leftrightarrows\mathcal{G}^{\prime}:f^{*}$ whose left adjoint maps finitely presentable objects of $\mathcal{G}^{\prime}$ to finitely presentable objects of $\mathcal{G}$.
Definition 2.3.1. We say that a full subcategory of a locally finitely presentable category is weakly definable if it is closed under products and directed colimits. Furthermore, a category is weakly definable if it is equivalent to a weakly definable subcategory of a locally finitely presentable category.
Definition 3.1.3. The free exact completion of a small lex category $\mathcal{C}$ is an exact category $\mathcal{C}_{ex/lex}$ together with a lex functor $h:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}_{ex/lex}$ such that $h$ has the following universal property: for any exact category $\mathcal{B}$, there is an equivalence of categories $-\circ h:\operatorname{Reg}(\mathcal{C}_{ex/lex},\mathcal{B})\to\operatorname{% Lex}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{B})$.
